[01]
name_jp = "ヒロシゲ36号 ～ Neo Super-Express"
name_en = "Hiroshige No.36 ~ Neo Super-Express"
comment8_en = "Though to Merry, the blonde girl, the extremely beautiful Japanesque scenery she saw while riding the Boyu Shinkansen Hiroshige was just dull visual stimulation."
comment8_jp = "だが、この卯酉新幹線『ヒロシゲ』から見えている極めて日本的な美しい情景も、金髪の少女、メリーにとっては退屈な映像刺激でしかなかった。"
comment7_en = "Besides Mt. Fuji, even the sea coast on the left side is so beautiful that even if it were acknowledged as a World Heritage Site a dozen of times over, it would not be enough. Such is the beauty of Tokaido."
comment7_jp = "富士どころか、左手に見える海岸だって、世界遺産に一ダースほど認定されてもまだ足りないくらい美しい。東海道はこんなにも美しいのだ。"
comment6_en = "Because of the efforts of the Mount Fuji Revival Association, it has finally been acknowledged as a World Heritage Site, but seen from the Hiroshige, it looks much more austere.\nOne of the reason is that because from the panoramic view from the Hiroshige, you never see any high buildings, power transmission lines or elevated railways."
comment6_jp = "富士山復興会の努力により、近年になって漸く世界遺産に認定された富士だが、ヒロシゲから見えているこの富士の方が何倍も荘厳に見える。\nというのも、ヒロシゲのパノラマビューから見ると、高層ビルも送電線も高架線も何一つ見つけられないのも一つの理由だろう。"
comment5_en = "It must have been 25 minutes since we left... Off in the distance, we can see Mount Fuji under an umbrella of clouds.\nIt appears so majestic, it almost looks like a sage or hermit lives on it."
comment5_jp = "出発から25分ほど経っただろうか、遠くに雲の傘を被った富士の山が見えた。\nまるで仙人でも住んでいそうな厳かな姿をしている。"
comment4_en = "A pleasant spring sunshine came in from the windows. This newest model of Shinkansen features a half-panoramic view in all the cars. Each car is entirely window except the ceiling and floor, in other words, the walls of the Shinkansen are the windows. It almost looks as if it were a test tube running on the railway. \nAt the left of the blonde girl facing in the direction opposite the train's was an endless, beautiful blue coast; at the right was a breathtaking vista of plains dotted with pine trees without a building in sight."
comment4_jp = "車窓から春の陽気が入ってくる。最新型のこの新幹線は全車両、半パノラマビューが一つの売りである。半パノラマビューとは上下を除いた全てが窓、つまり新幹線の壁は殆ど窓で、まるで大きなガラスの試験管が線路の上を走っている様な物だ。\n進行方向と反対に座っている金髪の少女の左手には、見渡す限りの美しい青の海岸、右手には建物一つ無い美しい平原と松林が広がっていた。"
comment3_en = "It had plenty of benches facing each other, accommodating up to four people. However, as they were all vacant, the two did not have any trouble finding an empty space. The morning outbound trains were extremely crowded with commuters, packed like sardines, yet the inbound for Tokyo trains were vacant, conveniently for them."
comment3_jp = "四人まで座れるボックス型の席には空きも多く見られ、二人で座っていたとしても相席を求められる事は無かった。朝の反対方向は芋洗いの様に通勤の人でごった返すが、東京行きは空いている。二人にとっては好都合だった。"
comment2_en = "The Hiroshige runs eastward, carrying two girls. It runs eastward, without the slightest turbulence."
comment2_jp = "ヒロシゲは二人を乗せて東へ走る。音もなく、揺れもなく、ただひたすら東に走る。"

[02]
name_jp = "53ミニッツの青い海"
name_en = "Blue Sea of 53 Minutes"
comment10_en = "The surprising thing is that the Shinkansen runs entirely underground in a straight line. From the departing station to the terminal, you cannot see sky, sea, mountain, forest, Sun nor Moon."
comment10_jp = "驚くべき事に、卯酉新幹線の全てが地下に、そして直線的に作られている。始点から終点まで、空も海も、山も森も、太陽も月も、何も見ることは出来ないのだ。"
comment9_en = "And the result was the creation of the Boyu Shinkansen Hiroshige. It runs between Kyoto and Tokyo in 53 minutes. This Shinkansen enabled the commuters to come and go between Kyoto and Tokyo, and it instantly became the main traffic artery of Japan."
comment9_jp = "そして完成したのが、京都―東京間を53分で繋ぐ卯酉新幹線『ヒロシゲ』である。この新幹線は、京都―東京を通勤圏内にし、あっという間に日本の大動脈となった。"
comment8_en = "After the relocation of the capital in the Jinki era, many people were faced with the necessity of coming and going between Tokyo and Kyoto. Suddenly the former Tokaido Shinkansen alone wasn't enough, so, in a pinch, the government started developing a new Shinkansen as soon as they could."
comment8_jp = "神亀の遷都が行われてから、大量の人間が東京と京都を行き来する必要が生まれた。旧東海道だけではすぐに交通インフラに限界が来て、政府は急ピッチに新しい新幹線の開発に取りかかったのだ。"
comment7_en = "   ...The Boyu Tokaido had been in operation since before they were born."
comment7_jp = "   ――卯酉東海道が出来たのは、二人が生まれる前の事である。"
comment6_en = "   \"I'm a celebrity.\""
comment6_jp = "   「セレブですわ」"
comment5_en = "      \"Don't talk like a spoiled kid. Nowadays, the only people who ride that are Tōhoku people, Indians and celebrities.\n      You might be as carefree as the Tōhoku people though.\""
comment5_jp = "      「何を贅沢言ってるのよ。旧東海道なんて、もう東北人とインド人とセレブくらいしか利用していないわよ。\n      ま、メリーは東北人並にのんびりしているかも知れないけどね」"
comment4_en = "   \"The Mt. Fuji above ground might not be this beautiful, but I wanted to see the genuine one.\n   I wish we could have taken the old Tokaido Shinkansen.\""
comment4_jp = "   「地上の富士はここまで綺麗じゃないかも知れないけど、それでも本物の方が見たかったわ。\n   これなら旧東海道新幹線の方が良かったなぁ」"
comment3_en = "      \"Maybe, but because of the pictures they display on the tunnels, it's much brighter than the subways in the past.\n      It feels just like we're above the ground, doesn't it?\""
comment3_jp = "      「これでもトンネルに映像が流れるようになって、昔の地下鉄よりは明るくなったのよ。\n      まるで地上みたいでしょ？」"
comment2_en = "   \"Hiroshige has large seats and runs very quickly, so it's convenient...\n   But to me, this 'fake' scenery through the Kaleido-screen is so boring.\""
comment2_jp = "   「ヒロシゲは席は広いし、早く着くし便利なんだけど――\n   カレイドスクリーンの『偽物の』景色しか見られないのは退屈ねぇ」"

[03]
name_jp = "竹取飛翔　～ Lunatic Princess"
name_en = "Bamboo Cutter Flight ~ Lunatic Princess"
comment10_en = "That's the ultimate feature of Boyu Tokaido that cost a fortune, the device called the Kaleido-screen."
comment10_jp = "それが、卯酉東海道最大の売りと予算を使った装置『カレイドスクリーン』だった。"
comment9_en = "In spite of it, the train presented them the sunlight from the windows like that above ground during the day and displayed the beautiful scenes of Mt. Fuji and the Pacific Ocean."
comment9_jp = "それでも、昼間の外と同じくらいの光が窓から射し、そして外には美しい富士と太平洋が映し出されていた。"
comment8_en = "She was also looking forward to the scenery on the way to Tokyo, but unfortunately, all of the trains on the Boyu Tokaido run under ground."
comment8_jp = "道中の景色も楽しみだったのだが、あいにく卯酉新幹線は全線完全地下の新幹線である。"
comment7_en = "Renko Usami and Maribel Hearn (Merry) decided to take a trip to Tokyo where Renko's parents live during their university's vacation.\nIt was more of an excuse to follow Renko on her trip for Higan, still she was looking forward to this trip so much because she had never been to Tokyo."
comment7_jp = "宇佐見蓮子とマエリベリー・ハーン（メリー）の二人は、大学の休みを利用して、蓮子の実家である東京へ旅行する事になった。\n旅行と言っても蓮子の彼岸参りに便乗するだけだが、まだ東京に行った事が無いメリーは、今回の東京旅行を非常に楽しみにしていた。"
comment6_en = "   \"One minute per station. At that pace, I'd go senile in three weeks. What a short journey that would be...\""
comment6_jp = "   「一分一泊ね。その調子なら三週間で老衰だわ。短い旅ねぇ」"
comment5_en = "      \"Oh, right. Have you heard this story?\n      The fact of the matter is the Hiroshige could make the trip less than 53 minutes if it went at its maximum speed, but they purposefully adjusted it to arrive at 53 minutes sharp.\""
comment5_jp = "      「そうそう、こんな話知ってる？\n      実は、ヒロシゲは最高速を出せば53分も掛からないらしいんだけど、わざわざ 53分になる様に調整したらしいよ？」"
comment4_en = "   \"Yes, yes. You're right.\n   Ooooh, I wonder if we can see the ancient rabbits making medicine on the fake full moon?\""
comment4_jp = "   「はいはい、そうですね。\n   あーあ、偽物の満月には、太古の兎が薬を搗いている姿が見えるのかなぁ」"
comment3_en = "      \"Though the travelling times has become shorter, a journey is still a journey. Sightseeing in Tokyo will be so much fun.\n      Unlike Kyoto, there are plenty of historical buildings in places like Shinjuku and Shibuya.\n      I thought it'd be better to spend less time travelling so we could sight-see more.\""
comment3_jp = "      「道中が短くなっただけで、旅行は旅行よ。東京観光巡りは面白いわよ？\n      京都と違って新宿とか渋谷とかには歴史を感じる建物も多いしね。\n      そういう観光の時間が増えたと思えば良いじゃない」"
comment2_en = "   \"It's nice to arrive in a flash, but aren't you bored with this fake scenery, Renko?\n   They even show a fake full moon during the nights when the real one is out.\n   The past Tokaido had 53 stations, while now, it only takes 53 minutes in spite of the increase in the distance from then.\n   It's impossible to call it a journey anymore.\""
comment2_jp = "   「あっという間に着くのは良いけど、こんな偽物の景色を見てるだけじゃ蓮子は退屈じゃないの？\n   夜は夜で空に浮かぶのは偽物の満月、ってのもなんかねぇ。\n   東海道も昔は53も宿場町があったというのに、今は53分で着いちゃうのよ？　昔よりも道のりも長いのに、\n   こうなっちゃうと、もう旅とは呼べないわよねぇ」"
comment11_jp = "(『東方文花帖』の『幻想の音覚』より)\n未だ、実際にこの眼でかぐや姫を見たことがない私は、竹取物語を読んで想像するしかなく、私なりな解釈で竹取物語終了後を曲にしてみました。\n満月の夜に現れる月の使者、それに抵抗する地上の人間。だが月の死者の前では為す術もなくやられてしまう。もう抵抗する気も失ったその時、地上の竹が光り始めて……現われたのは月の姫、かぐや姫だった。かぐやはこれ以上人間には迷惑をかけまいと、一人戦う決心をしたのである。\nという妄想は無く、大昔の日本の空にあったと言われる月と、空を翔る姫達をイメージして作曲しました。勿論遊び心も忘れずに、判る人だけに判るレトロさを入れて、何十年後になったときに最後まで心に残る曲になるよう頑張りました。"
comment11_en = "(Bohemian Archive in Japanese Red Music Columns)\nWhile I am someone who has yet to actually see Kaguya-hime, this song was not meant to represent The Tale of the Bamboo Cutter, but rather what happens after the story ends.\nThe messengers from the moon who reveal themselves only on nights of the full moon, and the ones they oppose, the humans on Earth. But those from the moon reach their wits' end and lose the will to fight. That's when the bamboo on Earth begins to glow... and the moon princess appears, that is, Kaguya-hime. Kaguya troubles the humans, and one man decides to fight her.\nMy image for this song is nothing that off-the-wall. It's more of the moon that was said to exist in Japan's sky a long time ago, and the princesses that fly through that sky. Of course, they still haven't lost their playful spirit, just like how some people still enjoy retro games. As I also want my songs to remain in people's minds decades from now, I will continue to do my best."

[04]
